<DOC><DOCNO> AP900420-0204 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-20-90 0004EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Australia-Floods     04-20 0148</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Australia-Floods,0152</SECOND><HEAD>30,000 in Outback Isolated by Floods</HEAD><DATELINE>BRISBANE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   More than 30,000 people in theAustralian outback have been isolated by near-record floods, policesaid Friday.   Farming districts in central and southern Queensland state werehardest hit by rising flood waters that followed three weeks ofheavy rain. Meterologists said the flooding was the worst in thearea for 40 years.   Most of the normally dusty roads in the region were awash,forcing animals to high ground and many families from their homes.   Families were evacuated from two towns, and another city hadbeen cut off from overland travel for nearly a month. Among thoseisolated were 80 campers near Carnarvon Gorge but they were in nodanger, a police spokesman said.   Two Royal Australian Air Force Caribou transport planes droppedsupplies to small rural communities Thursday and planned similarflights over the weekend.</TEXT></DOC>